SUMMARY: 90 Minutes of Innovation: Top Gun Meets a $2+ Billion Aviation Gam
 e-Changer 
LOCATION:The Pub
DESCRIPTION:Category: ‘Quin Chat\nPrice: Free\nAvailability: 32 spots lef
 t\nStatus: You are Confirmed\nEvent URL: https://members.thequinhouse.com/
 events/169177\n\n1:00PM Program\, 2:30PM Networking \nTwo frontiers. One 
 stage. Not to be missed. In this high-voltage edition of 90 Minutes of Inn
 ovation\, flight becomes more than a metaphor — it becomes a stress test
  for the future of AI\, defense\, climate innovation\, and human judgment 
 itself.\n\nJohn Werner — venture capitalist\, Forbes AI columnist\, and 
 Innovation Curator at The ’Quin House — convenes an extraordinary pair
 ing you won’t see anywhere else. A real-world Top Gun who has flown 80 c
 ombat missions\, 290 test missions\, and logged more than 2\,000 hours acr
 oss 30 aircraft — including the F-35\, F-15\, and F-16 — operating alo
 ngside AI in live\, high-stakes environments. And a leader helping build o
 ne of the most highly capitalized electric aviation companies in the world
 .\n\nFirst: Kristen Costello\n\nBuilding the Next Aviation System\n\nKrist
 en Costello is a pilot and executive at Vermont-based Beta Technologies\, 
 a New England aerospace company valued at more than $2 billion and backed 
 by over $1 billion from Fidelity\, Qatar Investment Authority\, Amazon’s
  Climate Pledge Fund\, GE Aerospace\, and others.\n\nBeta isn’t pitching
  a concept. It’s building a new aviation system. Founded by former Harva
 rd hockey player Kyle Clark — once told not to return to Vermont because
  “there was nothing there” — Beta has grown into one of the most amb
 itious aerospace companies on the planet. The company is developing all-el
 ectric aircraft for cargo\, medical logistics\, and passenger travel while
  simultaneously constructing a nationwide charging network. It has complet
 ed cross-country flights\, secured major commercial and defense partnershi
 ps\, and is advancing through the FAA’s rigorous certification process.\
 n\nThe breakthrough isn’t just the airplane. It’s the systems thinking
  — aircraft\, charging infrastructure\, certification\, pilot training\,
  and operations built in parallel. Not incremental change\, but a redesign
  of regional air mobility from propulsion to power grid. If it succeeds\, 
 it won’t just change how we fly. It will change where flying makes sense
 .\n\nThen: Tucker “Cinco” Hamilton\n\nWhere Humans and AI Share the Co
 ckpit\n\nThe evening shifts to contested airspace.\n\nRetired U.S. Air For
 ce Colonel and experimental fighter test pilot Tucker “Cinco” Hamilton
  — former Chief of AI Test and Operations for the U.S. Air Force and Spa
 ce Force — led the integration of AI-enabled autonomy into combat aircra
 ft. He has operated at the edge\, where algorithms and humans share the co
 ckpit in real-time\, high-consequence environments.\n\nHamilton brings aud
 iences inside moments few will ever experience: ejecting from a failing ai
 rcraft\, managing an engine fire at twice the speed of sound\, crash-landi
 ng a jet while fighting to keep it upright\, and flying combat missions ov
 er Afghanistan. For Hamilton\, AI is not theoretical. It is airborne. He h
 as confronted the defining questions of our era:\n\nWhen should a machine 
 be trusted?\n\nHow do you test systems that learn?\n\nWhat happens when AI
  evolves faster than doctrine?\n\nWho is accountable when autonomy acts?\n
 \nThis program also marks the debut of his new book\, Unlocking the Last 2
 0%\, on elite performance in an age of automation.\n\nAviation has always 
 previewed the future. Now it is revealing the operating system of the next
  century. The future is not humans replaced by machines. It is humans rede
 signed alongside them.\n\n*This event is complimentary and reserved for me
 mbers only. Light bites and refreshments will be served.
URL:https://members.thequinhouse.com/events/169177
